1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,333
<b>In May 2025, Britain signed</b>

2
00:00:02,333 --> 00:00:04,166
<b>away its last African colony.</b>

3
00:00:04,833 --> 00:00:06,033
<b>Headlines called it historic.</b>

4
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:07,400
<b>Mauritius finally got its</b>

5
00:00:07,400 --> 00:00:09,166
<b>islands back after 60 years.</b>

6
00:00:10,066 --> 00:00:10,633
<b>But here's what</b>

7
00:00:10,633 --> 00:00:11,699
<b>didn't make the headlines.</b>

8
00:00:12,166 --> 00:00:13,333
<b>The day before the</b>

9
00:00:13,333 --> 00:00:15,066
<b>meeting that started all this,</b>

10
00:00:15,333 --> 00:00:16,866
<b>a British official wrote a memo.</b>

11
00:00:17,433 --> 00:00:19,800
<b>September 22nd, 1965.</b>

12
00:00:20,533 --> 00:00:21,500
<b>His exact words.</b>

13
00:00:21,866 --> 00:00:24,033
<b>"The object is to frighten him with hope.</b>

14
00:00:24,766 --> 00:00:26,500
<b>Hope that he might get independence.</b>

15
00:00:27,199 --> 00:00:29,533
<b>Fright lest he might not unless he is</b>

16
00:00:29,533 --> 00:00:31,266
<b>sensible about the detachment of the</b>

17
00:00:31,266 --> 00:00:32,766
<b>Chagos Archipelago."</b>

18
00:00:33,566 --> 00:00:34,633
<b>The prime minister who</b>

19
00:00:34,633 --> 00:00:36,266
<b>signed the 2025 deal,</b>

20
00:00:36,966 --> 00:00:38,833
<b>his father was the man sitting across</b>

21
00:00:38,833 --> 00:00:41,099
<b>from Harold Wilson in 1965,</b>

22
00:00:41,733 --> 00:00:44,033
<b>being told to hand over those islands or</b>

23
00:00:44,033 --> 00:00:45,300
<b>forget about independence.</b>

24
00:00:46,666 --> 00:00:49,233
<b>60 years later, the son gets them back.</b>

25
00:00:49,766 --> 00:00:50,400
<b>Sort of.</b>

26
00:00:50,966 --> 00:00:51,733
<b>Because the two thousand</b>

27
00:00:51,733 --> 00:00:53,133
<b>people Britain deported,</b>

28
00:00:53,699 --> 00:00:55,266
<b>they're still not allowed to go home.</b>

29
00:00:55,733 --> 00:00:58,033
<b>And Mauritius agreed to keep it that way.</b>

30
00:00:59,133 --> 00:01:00,866
<b>So, what made these islands worth</b>

31
00:01:00,866 --> 00:01:01,566
<b>threatening a</b>

32
00:01:01,566 --> 00:01:02,900
<b>country's independence over?</b>

33
00:01:03,933 --> 00:01:05,233
<b>Diego Garcia sits in the</b>

34
00:01:05,233 --> 00:01:06,366
<b>middle of the Indian Ocean,</b>

35
00:01:06,733 --> 00:01:07,300
<b>within striking</b>

36
00:01:07,300 --> 00:01:08,633
<b>distance of the Persian Gulf.</b>

37
00:01:09,366 --> 00:01:10,966
<b>South Asia, East Africa,</b>

38
00:01:11,733 --> 00:01:12,366
<b>one of the best</b>

39
00:01:12,366 --> 00:01:13,933
<b>natural harbors in the world.</b>

40
00:01:15,033 --> 00:01:17,566
<b>By the 1960s, the Pentagon was watching</b>

41
00:01:17,566 --> 00:01:19,666
<b>colonies become independent nations.</b>

42
00:01:20,766 --> 00:01:22,333
<b>Nations that didn't always want American</b>

43
00:01:22,333 --> 00:01:23,633
<b>bases on their soil.</b>

44
00:01:24,233 --> 00:01:26,366
<b>They needed somewhere remote, somewhere</b>

45
00:01:26,366 --> 00:01:28,000
<b>without political complications.</b>

46
00:01:29,266 --> 00:01:31,733
<b>The phrase "exclusive control without</b>

47
00:01:31,733 --> 00:01:33,800
<b>local inhabitants" is</b>

48
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:35,133
<b>from the planning documents.</b>

49
00:01:35,633 --> 00:01:37,266
<b>The goal wasn't just a military base.</b>

50
00:01:37,866 --> 00:01:38,933
<b>It was a base with no</b>

51
00:01:38,933 --> 00:01:40,599
<b>voters, no journalists,</b>

52
00:01:41,300 --> 00:01:42,266
<b>no one who might ask</b>

53
00:01:42,266 --> 00:01:43,933
<b>questions at the United Nations.</b>

54
00:01:45,133 --> 00:01:46,366
<b>There was just one problem.</b>

55
00:01:46,766 --> 00:01:49,833
<b>About 1,500 people already lived there.</b>

56
00:01:50,366 --> 00:01:51,733
<b>The Chagossians had been on</b>

57
00:01:51,733 --> 00:01:53,066
<b>those islands for generations.</b>

58
00:01:53,599 --> 00:01:55,766
<b>Descendants from enslaved and indentured</b>

59
00:01:55,766 --> 00:01:57,900
<b>laborers with their own distinct culture.</b>

60
00:01:59,066 --> 00:01:59,933
<b>So, Britain decided</b>

61
00:01:59,933 --> 00:02:01,099
<b>to solve that problem.</b>

62
00:02:01,599 --> 00:02:04,233
<b>First on paper, then in reality.</b>

63
00:02:05,133 --> 00:02:07,099
<b>September 23rd, 1965.</b>

64
00:02:07,866 --> 00:02:10,033
<b>The morning after that memo was written,</b>

65
00:02:10,833 --> 00:02:12,533
<b>Harold Wilson met with</b>

66
00:02:12,533 --> 00:02:14,633
<b>Seewoosagur Ramgoolam,</b>

67
00:02:14,866 --> 00:02:16,433
<b>the premier of Mauritius at</b>

68
00:02:16,433 --> 00:02:17,866
<b>Lancaster House in London.</b>

69
00:02:18,599 --> 00:02:20,766
<b>And Wilson made the situation clear.</b>

70
00:02:21,699 --> 00:02:23,466
<b>The premier and his colleagues could</b>

71
00:02:23,466 --> 00:02:24,833
<b>return to Mauritius,</b>

72
00:02:24,833 --> 00:02:27,566
<b>either with independence or without it.</b>

73
00:02:28,266 --> 00:02:29,266
<b>That is a direct quote</b>

74
00:02:29,266 --> 00:02:30,366
<b>from the meeting notes.</b>

75
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:32,433
<b>"Give us the islands or</b>

76
00:02:32,433 --> 00:02:33,666
<b>you don't become a country."</b>

77
00:02:34,599 --> 00:02:36,599
<b>Now, think about what's happening here.</b>

78
00:02:37,133 --> 00:02:39,066
<b>Ramgoulam isn't negotiating as the leader</b>

79
00:02:39,066 --> 00:02:40,333
<b>of an independent nation.</b>

80
00:02:40,833 --> 00:02:42,966
<b>He is a colonial subject, sitting across</b>

81
00:02:42,966 --> 00:02:43,766
<b>from the government,</b>

82
00:02:44,133 --> 00:02:45,266
<b>that still controls his</b>

83
00:02:45,266 --> 00:02:47,233
<b>country, being told what to do.</b>

84
00:02:48,166 --> 00:02:50,233
<b>The ICJ would later apply what they</b>

85
00:02:50,233 --> 00:02:51,366
<b>called "heightened</b>

86
00:02:51,366 --> 00:02:52,666
<b>scrutiny" to this moment.</b>

87
00:02:53,366 --> 00:02:54,133
<b>Their conclusion?</b>

88
00:02:55,133 --> 00:02:56,633
<b>Britain's so-called consent from</b>

89
00:02:56,633 --> 00:02:58,199
<b>Mauritius was not based on</b>

90
00:02:58,199 --> 00:02:59,833
<b>the free and genuine expression</b>

91
00:02:59,833 --> 00:03:01,500
<b>of the will of the people concerned.</b>

92
00:03:02,533 --> 00:03:03,833
<b>Britain paid £3 million.</b>

93
00:03:04,900 --> 00:03:07,333
<b>And on November 8th, 1965,</b>

94
00:03:08,133 --> 00:03:09,433
<b>three years before Mauritius</b>

95
00:03:09,433 --> 00:03:10,766
<b>would even become independent,</b>

96
00:03:11,300 --> 00:03:12,966
<b>the UK passed the British</b>

97
00:03:12,966 --> 00:03:14,933
<b>Indian Ocean Territory Order.</b>

98
00:03:16,033 --> 00:03:18,800
<b>Using an archaic royal prerogative, no</b>

99
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:20,433
<b>parliamentary vote required.</b>

100
00:03:20,833 --> 00:03:22,699
<b>They carved out the Chagos Archipelago</b>

101
00:03:22,699 --> 00:03:25,199
<b>and created a brand new colony.</b>

102
00:03:26,033 --> 00:03:28,400
<b>The paperwork was done, now they just had</b>

103
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:29,500
<b>to empty the islands.</b>

104
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:31,133
<b>The deportation happened in</b>

105
00:03:31,133 --> 00:03:33,166
<b>stages and it was calculated.</b>

106
00:03:34,199 --> 00:03:35,900
<b>The only way between Chagos</b>

107
00:03:35,900 --> 00:03:37,933
<b>and Mauritius was by cargo ship.</b>

108
00:03:38,599 --> 00:03:40,633
<b>So, starting in 1969,</b>

109
00:03:41,333 --> 00:03:43,566
<b>Chagossians who left the islands to visit</b>

110
00:03:43,566 --> 00:03:44,833
<b>family, for example,</b>

111
00:03:45,466 --> 00:03:46,966
<b>found that they couldn't come back.</b>

112
00:03:47,300 --> 00:03:49,466
<b>Their work contracts had expired.</b>

113
00:03:50,066 --> 00:03:51,500
<b>The ship wouldn't take them.</b>

114
00:03:51,933 --> 00:03:53,533
<b>Rita Bancoult was one of them.</b>

115
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:54,900
<b>A steamship company</b>

116
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:56,766
<b>representative told her directly,</b>

117
00:03:57,366 --> 00:03:58,966
<b>"Your island has been sold.</b>

118
00:03:59,333 --> 00:04:00,733
<b>You will never go there again."</b>

119
00:04:01,133 --> 00:04:03,133
<b>Then the supplies started drying up.</b>

120
00:04:03,466 --> 00:04:05,133
<b>Less food, less medicine.</b>

121
00:04:05,966 --> 00:04:07,466
<b>The message wasn't subtle.</b>

122
00:04:08,199 --> 00:04:09,833
<b>Leave or starve.</b>

123
00:04:10,166 --> 00:04:11,733
<b>Those who stayed got it clearer.</b>

124
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:15,233
<b>Chagossians reported being told they'd be</b>

125
00:04:15,233 --> 00:04:18,033
<b>bombed or shot if they refused to go.</b>

126
00:04:18,833 --> 00:04:20,233
<b>And then there were the dogs.</b>

127
00:04:21,300 --> 00:04:23,033
<b>Before the final deportations,</b>

128
00:04:23,433 --> 00:04:24,599
<b>British agents rounded</b>

129
00:04:24,599 --> 00:04:25,966
<b>up Chagossians' pets.</b>

130
00:04:26,666 --> 00:04:28,366
<b>Hundreds of dogs, herded</b>

131
00:04:28,366 --> 00:04:29,900
<b>them into a sealed shed</b>

132
00:04:29,966 --> 00:04:32,266
<b>and ran exhaust fumes from military</b>

133
00:04:32,266 --> 00:04:33,733
<b>vehicles into the building.</b>

134
00:04:34,300 --> 00:04:35,933
<b>They gassed them and</b>

135
00:04:35,933 --> 00:04:36,966
<b>then burned the bodies.</b>

136
00:04:37,566 --> 00:04:38,766
<b>The families waiting to be</b>

137
00:04:38,766 --> 00:04:40,400
<b>deported watched it happen.</b>

138
00:04:40,966 --> 00:04:43,666
<b>Between 1967 and 1973,</b>

139
00:04:44,133 --> 00:04:44,766
<b>somewhere between</b>

140
00:04:44,766 --> 00:04:47,199
<b>1,500 and 2,000 Chagossians</b>

141
00:04:47,333 --> 00:04:48,766
<b>were left on docks in</b>

142
00:04:48,766 --> 00:04:50,333
<b>Mauritius and the Seychelles.</b>

143
00:04:50,900 --> 00:04:51,766
<b>No housing arranged,</b>

144
00:04:52,300 --> 00:04:54,266
<b>no jobs and no support.</b>

145
00:04:54,833 --> 00:04:56,566
<b>One survivor put it this way,</b>

146
00:04:56,933 --> 00:04:58,233
<b>"It's as if I was pulled from</b>

147
00:04:58,233 --> 00:05:00,233
<b>my paradise to put me in hell."</b>

148
00:05:00,766 --> 00:05:02,666
<b>For decades Mauritius pushed</b>

149
00:05:02,666 --> 00:05:04,333
<b>this through international law.</b>

150
00:05:04,766 --> 00:05:07,233
<b>And in 2019, they got their ruling.</b>

151
00:05:08,233 --> 00:05:09,766
<b>I went through the ICJ opinion.</b>

152
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:11,766
<b>All 56 pages.</b>

153
00:05:12,333 --> 00:05:13,800
<b>The language isn't ambiguous.</b>

154
00:05:14,266 --> 00:05:16,733
<b>13 judges to one found that Britain's</b>

155
00:05:16,733 --> 00:05:18,333
<b>decolonization of Mauritius</b>

156
00:05:18,466 --> 00:05:20,133
<b>was not lawfully completed</b>

157
00:05:20,133 --> 00:05:21,633
<b>when they carved out Chagos.</b>

158
00:05:22,166 --> 00:05:23,666
<b>The court's exact words,</b>

159
00:05:24,199 --> 00:05:25,766
<b>"The United Kingdom's continued</b>

160
00:05:25,766 --> 00:05:28,033
<b>administration of the Chagos Archipelago</b>

161
00:05:28,233 --> 00:05:29,566
<b>constitutes a wrongful act</b>

162
00:05:29,599 --> 00:05:30,566
<b>entailing the international</b>

163
00:05:30,566 --> 00:05:32,199
<b>responsibility of that state."</b>

164
00:05:32,533 --> 00:05:34,633
<b>Now, to be fair to the UK position,</b>

165
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:36,633
<b>and I want to present the strongest</b>

166
00:05:36,633 --> 00:05:37,866
<b>version of their argument,</b>

167
00:05:38,433 --> 00:05:40,466
<b>Diego Garcia isn't just any base.</b>

168
00:05:41,099 --> 00:05:43,733
<b>B-52s flew from that atoll during the</b>

169
00:05:43,733 --> 00:05:44,766
<b>Afghanistan invasion.</b>

170
00:05:45,666 --> 00:05:46,766
<b>Prepositioned ships</b>

171
00:05:46,766 --> 00:05:48,166
<b>supplied the Gulf War.</b>

172
00:05:48,933 --> 00:05:50,666
<b>The facility supports GPS,</b>

173
00:05:51,366 --> 00:05:52,866
<b>nuclear test monitoring and</b>

174
00:05:52,866 --> 00:05:54,666
<b>counter-piracy operations.</b>

175
00:05:55,333 --> 00:05:56,766
<b>Defence experts call it</b>

176
00:05:56,966 --> 00:05:57,733
<b>the single most</b>

177
00:05:57,733 --> 00:05:59,366
<b>important military facility</b>

178
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:00,300
<b>between the</b>

179
00:06:00,300 --> 00:06:01,533
<b>Mediterranean and the Pacific.</b>

180
00:06:02,033 --> 00:06:02,966
<b>And the one dissenting</b>

181
00:06:02,966 --> 00:06:04,933
<b>judge, Joan Donoghue,</b>

182
00:06:05,166 --> 00:06:06,800
<b>made a serious legal argument.</b>

183
00:06:07,166 --> 00:06:08,133
<b>She said this was a</b>

184
00:06:08,133 --> 00:06:09,833
<b>bilateral sovereignty dispute.</b>

185
00:06:10,300 --> 00:06:11,266
<b>And by ruling on it,</b>

186
00:06:11,566 --> 00:06:13,866
<b>the ICJ was circumventing Britain's right</b>

187
00:06:13,866 --> 00:06:15,966
<b>to refuse judicial settlement.</b>

188
00:06:16,366 --> 00:06:17,266
<b>In her words,</b>

189
00:06:17,533 --> 00:06:19,433
<b>"The court's decision undermines the</b>

190
00:06:19,433 --> 00:06:20,333
<b>integrity of the</b>

191
00:06:20,333 --> 00:06:21,766
<b>court's judicial function."</b>

192
00:06:22,300 --> 00:06:22,866
<b>But here's the</b>

193
00:06:22,866 --> 00:06:24,066
<b>problem with that argument.</b>

194
00:06:24,566 --> 00:06:26,066
<b>The ICJ didn't treat this</b>

195
00:06:26,066 --> 00:06:27,500
<b>as a simple land dispute.</b>

196
00:06:27,933 --> 00:06:29,833
<b>An obligation owed to the entire</b>

197
00:06:29,833 --> 00:06:30,766
<b>international community.</b>

198
00:06:31,333 --> 00:06:33,066
<b>And when 116 countries</b>

199
00:06:33,066 --> 00:06:35,033
<b>voted for Britain to withdraw,</b>

200
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:37,666
<b>and only 6 countries they voted against,</b>

201
00:06:37,933 --> 00:06:39,133
<b>bilateral dispute doesn't</b>

202
00:06:39,133 --> 00:06:40,266
<b>quite describe it anymore.</b>

203
00:06:40,666 --> 00:06:41,566
<b>London's response.</b>

204
00:06:42,133 --> 00:06:43,933
<b>"The UK representative said Britain had</b>

205
00:06:43,933 --> 00:06:45,466
<b>no doubt about our sovereignty</b>

206
00:06:46,166 --> 00:06:47,500
<b>and dismissed the ruling as</b>

207
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:49,366
<b>merely an advisory opinion.</b>

208
00:06:49,366 --> 00:06:51,933
<b>The six-month deadline came and went.</b>

209
00:06:52,566 --> 00:06:53,266
<b>Britain stayed.</b>

210
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:54,666
<b>Nothing changed.</b>

211
00:06:55,066 --> 00:06:59,099
<b>Until 2025, May 22nd, 2025,</b>

212
00:06:59,300 --> 00:07:01,366
<b>Britain finally signs over sovereignty.</b>

213
00:07:02,300 --> 00:07:04,000
<b>Mauritius gets its territory back.</b>

214
00:07:04,300 --> 00:07:05,400
<b>Decolonization complete.</b>

215
00:07:05,866 --> 00:07:07,900
<b>Not quite, because when you read the</b>

216
00:07:07,900 --> 00:07:09,533
<b>treaty, it's more complicated.</b>

217
00:07:10,133 --> 00:07:11,633
<b>And this is where Mauritius</b>

218
00:07:11,633 --> 00:07:13,099
<b>deserves some scrutiny too.</b>

219
00:07:13,733 --> 00:07:15,833
<b>Diego Garcia, the island with the base,</b>

220
00:07:16,133 --> 00:07:17,633
<b>the whole reason any of this happened,</b>

221
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,066
<b>stays under US-UK control for 99 years,</b>

222
00:07:21,366 --> 00:07:23,733
<b>with an option to extend for another 40,</b>

223
00:07:24,199 --> 00:07:26,133
<b>and potentially after that.</b>

224
00:07:26,566 --> 00:07:27,733
<b>Britain pays Mauritius</b>

225
00:07:27,733 --> 00:07:30,166
<b>about £101 million per year,</b>

226
00:07:30,666 --> 00:07:31,833
<b>over the full term,</b>

227
00:07:32,133 --> 00:07:33,666
<b>roughly £3.4 billion.</b>

228
00:07:34,733 --> 00:07:35,400
<b>But here's what</b>

229
00:07:35,400 --> 00:07:36,400
<b>doesn't make the headlines.</b>

230
00:07:36,933 --> 00:07:38,233
<b>The Chagossians, the people</b>

231
00:07:38,233 --> 00:07:39,733
<b>who were actually deported,</b>

232
00:07:40,333 --> 00:07:41,366
<b>weren't at the table.</b>

233
00:07:42,033 --> 00:07:44,333
<b>A UK spokesperson confirmed they could</b>

234
00:07:44,333 --> 00:07:45,900
<b>not be part of the negotiations</b>

235
00:07:46,433 --> 00:07:47,800
<b>as they were conducted on a</b>

236
00:07:47,800 --> 00:07:48,966
<b>state-to-state basis.</b>

237
00:07:50,133 --> 00:07:50,699
<b>Two governments</b>

238
00:07:50,699 --> 00:07:52,433
<b>deciding the future of islands</b>

239
00:07:52,533 --> 00:07:53,766
<b>that belonged to</b>

240
00:07:53,766 --> 00:07:54,833
<b>neither of them originally,</b>

241
00:07:55,466 --> 00:07:56,333
<b>and the people who lived</b>

242
00:07:56,333 --> 00:07:58,166
<b>there, they were not invited.</b>

243
00:07:58,633 --> 00:07:59,766
<b>And when you read the treaty,</b>

244
00:08:00,233 --> 00:08:01,699
<b>there it is in black and white.</b>

245
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:03,500
<b>Mauritius can resettle</b>

